{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}} {{for|the California politician|Dan W. Emmett}} [[Image:Dan Emmett portrait.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=Head shot of an older man with white hair and moustache, dressed in tuxedo and bow tie.|Photograph of Dan Emmett in his later years, taken from the belongings of Ben and Lew Snowden of Clinton, Knox County, Ohio.]]
'''Daniel Decatur "Dan" Emmett''' (October 29, 1815 – June 28, 1904)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/5971798 Findagrave: Dan Emmett]</ref> was an American songwriter, entertainer, and founder of the first troupe of the [[blackface]] minstrel tradition, the [[Virginia Minstrels]].<ref>''The Oxford Companion to Music'', Oxford University Press 1955 ([[Percy A. Scholes]], ed.)</ref>
==Biography== Of [[Irish American|Irish ancestry]], Dan Emmett was born in [[Mount Vernon, Ohio]], then a frontier region. Growing up with little formal education, he learned popular tunes from his musical mother, and taught himself to play the fiddle. At age 13, he became an apprentice printer and enlisted in the United States Army. He became an expert fifer and drummer at Newport Barracks, [[Newport, Kentucky]], and published his own Fifer’s and Drummer’s Guide in 1862 in cooperation with [[George G. Bruce]]. After receiving his discharge from the army on July 8, 1835, he joined a Cincinnati circus. In 1840–1842 he toured with Angevine and other circuses as a blackface banjoist and singer.<ref>[http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/grove/music/08773?q=dan+emmett&article_section=all&search=article&pos=1&_start=1#firsthit at www.oxfordmusiconline.com]</ref> Emmett was a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSLCS7hg-DEC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Daniel%20Emmett&f=false|title=The Ku Klux Klan in Mississippi : a history|last=1951–|first=Newton, Michael,|date=2010|publisher=McFarland & Co|year=|isbn=9780786457045|location=Jefferson, N.C.|pages=95|oclc=567910513}}</ref>
In association with [[Billy Whitlock]], [[Dick Pelham]], and [[Frank Brower]], he organized the [[Virginia Minstrels]], which made their first appearance before a paying audience at the Chatham Theatre in New York City in 1843.<ref>Whitlock, who detailed the beginnings of the group, stated that the event was a benefit for Pelham. See Lawrence Hutton, "The Negro on the Stage," ''Harpers New Monthly Magazine'', June 1889, p. 140. Such an event occurred on January 31. See ''The New York Herald'', January 31, 1843, p. 3. The following day the ''Herald'' reported that the troupe would be appearing at the Bowery Amphitheatre, and an advertisement in February 6 issue refers to their first performance that evening.</ref>
[[Image:Dan Emmett in blackface.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Photo of a man in blackface dressed in nondescript clothes behind a small table with a top hat at his feet.|left|thumb|130px|Photograph of Dan Emmett in blackface, probably early 1860s.]] Although blackface performance, in which white men painted their faces and hands black and impersonated caricatures of African-American men and women, was already an established performance mode at that time&mdash;[[Thomas D. Rice]] had created the character of [[Jump Jim Crow|Jim Crow]] nearly a decade earlier, and blackface had been widely popular ever since<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitt.edu/~amerimus/Minstrelsy.html |title=Blackface Minstrelsy |publisher=Center for American Music, [[University of Pittsburgh]] |accessdate=July 15, 2015}}</ref>&mdash;Emmett's group is said to be the first to "black up" an entire band rather than one or two performers.{{cn|date=October 2018}} The group's full-length blackface performance is generally considered to have been the first true [[minstrel show]]: previous blackface acts were usually either an [[entr'acte]] for a play or one of many acts in a comic variety show.{{cn|date=October 2018}}
Emmett is traditionally credited with writing the famous song "[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]]." The story that he related about its composition varied each time he told it, but the main points were that he composed the song in New York City while a member of [[Bryant's Minstrels]]. The song was first performed by Emmett and the Bryants at [[Mechanics' Hall, New York City|Mechanics' Hall]] in New York City on April 4, 1859. The song became a runaway hit, especially in [[Southern United States|the South]], and the piece for which Emmett was most well known. Emmett himself reportedly told a fellow minstrel: "If I had known to what use they [Southerners] were going to put my song, I will be damned if I'd have written it."<ref>Letter from Col. T. Allston Brown to T.C. De Leon. Published in De Leon, ''Belles, Beaux, and Brains'' and quoted in Nathan 275.</ref> After the South began using his song as a rallying call, Emmett wrote the fife-and-drum manual for the Union Army. Emmett's song was a favorite of President [[Abraham Lincoln]], who said after the war ended in 1865, "I have always thought that 'Dixie' was one of the best tunes I ever heard... I insisted yesterday that we had fairly captured it."<ref>Speech given on April 10, 1865 and quoted in Hall 10.</ref>
Another writer named [[William Shakespeare Hays]] (1837–1907) (pen name: Will S. Hays) claimed to be its true author.<ref>Abel, E. Lawrence (2000). ''Singing the New Nation: How Music Shaped the Confederacy, 1861–1865''. Mechanicsburg, Pennsylvania: Stackpole Books, p. 47.</ref> Members of the [[Snowden Family Band|Snowden Family]] of [[Knox County, Ohio]], have also been named as writers of the song.<ref>Sacks, Howard L. and Sacks, Judith Rose (1993). ''Way up North in Dixie: A Black Family's Claim to the Confederate Anthem''. Washington: Smithsonian Institution Press, p. 3.</ref>
== Death and posthumous recognition == After a tour that was notably successful in the South, Emmett retired to his hometown of Mount Vernon in 1888<ref>Occasionally taking part in performances: "Dan Emmett, whenever he is physically able and can get the chance, 'rosins his bow' for a dance party in Chicago."''New York Times'', July 10, 1887: 'Drop-Curtain Monographs'</ref> where he died on June 28, 1904, aged 88 years. From 1893 to the time of his death, he was aided by a weekly allowance from the [[Actors Fund|Actors Fund of America]]. Emmett was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1970. A [[biographical film]] of his life was produced in 1943, titled [[Dixie (film)|''Dixie'']]. Starring [[Bing Crosby]] and [[Dorothy Lamour]], it is a [[musical film|musical]] directed by [[A. Edward Sutherland]].
Numerous schools, businesses, and other institutions in Mount Vernon, Ohio, are named after Emmett. The official memorial to him is a large boulder with a placard attached located in front of the Knox County Historical Museum.<ref>[http://www.mountvernonnews.com/local/06/05/15/dan.emmett.html Dan Emmett memorial re-dedicated | mountvernonnews.com<!-- bot-generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929094306/http://www.mountvernonnews.com/local/06/05/15/dan.emmett.html|date=September 29, 2007}} at www.mountvernonnews.com</ref>
Emmett published at least 30 songs between 1843 and 1865, most of which are banjo tunes or walk-arounds. Between 1859 and 1869, he composed another 25 tunes that are in manuscript at the Ohio Historical Society in [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>[http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/grove/music/08773?q=dan+emmett&article_section=all&search=article&pos=1&_start=1#firsthit at www.oxfordmusiconline.com]</ref>
